ns, including the language regions, making if harder to learn new languages after a certain critical point. This is why it is more difficult to learn a second language when you are older. In fact, when you learn a language as an adult the right hemisphere (or whichever is not where language is lateralized for the individual) is more involved in the process, as the language regions are less plastic then the used to be.%0a%3c %0a%3c Over the years, neurolinguistic research has changed a great deal. Most of the early research in this field was done by studying the production and comprehension of individuals suffering from aphasia. As technology advanced, CAT scans and CT scans could also be used to supplement these observational studies, but they could not provide much detail as to the damage/functioning of the brain and its activity. Currently, much of the research done regarding brain activity is done using fMRIs, EEGs, and MEGs. This allows researchers to measure blood flow to certain regions of the brain, and thus activity, as well as the electrical and magnetic signal that neurons use to communicate. As technology improves, the research involving neurolinguistics will also improve, allowing for us to create a better understanding of how we learn, store, and use language.%0a%3c %0a%3c Source: https://www.linguisticsociety.org/resource/neurolinguistics%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Expansions:%0a%3c [[#expansions]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#expansionsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%3c %0a%3c (:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:else:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Comments%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c (:section: C:)%0a%3c (:Category: Varia:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
